name: Rahman and Gibran Dalrymple

We continued to root for Seattle the year the Raiders became the first wildcard team to win the Super Bowl. (Seattle beat them twice that year but lost the wildcard game in overtime) We were fans during the strike year that they came in strong late in the season and the Giants were grateful Seattle did not make the playoffs. We were fans every time Seattle showed promise and were very upset at the referee calls in their first Super Bowl appearance. Up here in the white mountains if Arizina, we are surrounded by Cardinals and Denver fans. It is so gratifying the Seahawks have finally redeemed our devotion and shown true dynasty potential. Go Hawks! repeat... Then three peat!

name: Luke Beasley
note:
I grew up in Helena, MT.  My father and brothers and I would take annual trips to Seattle on a weekend when both the DAWGS and HAWKS were in town so we could catch a DAWG game on Saturday and a HAWKS game on Sunday.  These trips were always awesome and a great family bonding time for us.

My father grew up in Seattle and lived on Queen Anne Hill.  He graduated from Queen Anne High (when it still existed).  So consequently, my brothers and I grew up Seattle everything fans.

I now live in Bismarck, ND with my family.  I haven't been to the CLink since 2005 when we moved from Western Montana to North Dakota.  However, my kids both love the HAWKS now and we represent the 12's from the flats of North Dakota now.  Someday soon I plan to bring my kids and wife to the CLink to experience the sheer awesomeness of HAWKS Gameday.

Until then, we will continue to support the HAWKS from a far.

In addition, my two brothers are driving from Helena MT to Seatown for tomorrow nights opener as I type this.  Super jealous, but also excited for them.  They were also in attendance for the niner game in September last season, as well as both playoff games.  

So in conclusion, the HAWKS are a Beasley family affair.  Go HAWKS!

name: Jeff Mathews
note: I have been a Seahawks fan since I can remember.  I grew up in Las Vegas and we don't have any professional sports teams.  I got into the Hawks at a very early age because both of my parents are from the Seattle area.  I was fortunate enough to be featured in the "who's coming to the game" article on seahawks.com for last season divisional playoff game against the Saints.  I at front Row in the endzone beneath the Hawks' Nest for that game.  I remember how cold and wet it was and it made the atmosphere even better.  I was asked a question in that article, what was my favorite Seahawks' moment, I answered that question with watching the Hawks won the NFC Championship the first time against Carolina.  It's safe to say I have a new Hawks favorite, and that was running around my Las Vegas apartment screaming like a child after "the tip" by Sherman and and pick by Smith.  My best friend and I watched the game together, his name is Blaine and he is a huge Niners fan. I will never forget him ripping of his Kaepernick jersey and laying face down on the floor for ten minutes expressing how much he hates the UNR product (as we are both UNLV Rebels fans).  This is what Seahawks football does to us 12's.  It engulfs us emotionally and makes us feel like we are a part of the team and it's the best feeling in the world.  I'm so proud to part of the best fan base in the entire world.  Loud. Proud. TWELVE.

After years of not-so-good teams and moving around the country, my faith the Seahawks didn't waiver.  And for that, I, and so many others like me, fans old and new, have been rewarded the last few years under Pete Carroll with the ultimate prize:  a Super Bowl championship for a city and a region long whose sports teams were long associated with mediocrity. note:
I *WISH* I was a season ticket holder! What a dream!

It's funny, the first time I went to an NFL game *AND* saw the Seahawks play live, was in December '95, when I was a senior in high school, living in South Dakota, of all places. My best friend, Jamie, had a wonderful aunt & uncle in Denver with season tickets on the 50 yard line. Since the Broncos were "...*only* playing the Seahawks." that weekend, they offered me & Jamie the tickets!

It was relatively easy for J to take off, since she was a Sophomore at Black Hills State University in Spearfish, South Dakota. It wasn't nearly as easy for me; but, when she showed up in her Jeep Wrangler, parked in front of my high school, that Friday, at lunch, offering a road trip and FOOTBALL, I 
didn't think twice!

I went home "sick" from school, and had to call in "sick" to my after school 
and weekend job at a fast food place I usually worked 6p-close, 5-6 days a week, for nearly two years. They weren't used to having to find someone to fill in for me, but had a hard time arguing that I had plenty of sick time!

Less than an hour later, we were on the road to Denver, Colorado! J's aunt and uncle were die-hard Broncos fans, of course; it was still the 
John Elway era, after all. So, I wore the jersey and fan clothes they lent me, and they threw us a terrific tail-gate party, especially after learning it was my first NFL game!

Still, though I'd move around a lot, and had yet to even visit the Pacific Northwest, Seattle had been on my list of places to live, in the future, for years; so, though I'd have been pretty scared, at the time, to dress like a Seahawks fan amongst the throng of Broncos fans, I told J I was secretly rooting for the "underdogs". She said, "That's cool, but PLEASE keep it a secret!"

For the most part, I thought the Broncos fans were supercool people, and 
the tailgate parties were outrageous! However, on our way in to the stadium, I saw someone holding a long stick with a fake, life-sized 
Seahawks player, hanging from a noose; I was REALLY offended, on behalf of the Seahawks, and strengthened my resolve to direct all of my positive energy to the 'Hawks!

I didn't know ANY of the players; both of my parents had been born and/or raised in Texas, so I'd been raised a Dallas Cowboy fan, even though I'd never lived there. I WAS a diehard Cowboys' fan for a verrry long time. 

One of the things I loved most about them? It was their constant ability to come from behind and win! The 4th quarter was nearly always my favorite, however nail-bitingly close, because when they had nothing to lose, they'd start bringing on the crazy and pull off a victory that would confound the other team!

So, on that bitter cold day in December, when the Seahawks were shut out for most of the first half, just finally getting a field goal before actually going into the half, I had and still have, a lot of faith in the power of the halftime locker room speech; I even think that *not* being ahead at the start of the second half, is one of the best incentives for a team to rally and get it together; to blow the other team's mind for the rest of the game!

The 'Hawks didn't disapoint...ME, anyway! Antonio Edwards scored their 
first touchdown, with an 83 yard fumble return in the 3rd quarter! They took control with THREE more touchdowns in the 4th quarter, to the 
Broncos' single 1-yd rush touchdown, by Elway, himself, and the Seahawks WON: 31-28! The Broncos and their fans were in shock, and I had to bite my tongue a lot that day!

I had no idea that I'd actually end up in the Seattle area, but, I thought they were a team with a lot of potential, even then. Even when I did move out here, it was very difficult to let go of my beloved Cowboys, no matter how poorly they were doing.

It was at a Cowboys vs. Seahawks game watching party, that I vowed, in front of about 20-30 Seahawks fans, that whichever team won, I'd be that team's fan, from then on, and stop waffling. It was a crazy game; we had no idea who was going to win! But, the 'Hawks pulled it off! An interception with 5 seconds left and subsequent 50-yd field goal confirmed the win!

And, I'll admit, I was actually relieved; I'm a loyal fan, so it was difficult to give up the Cowboys, even though I'd been living in the Puget Sound area for several years, by then. I WANTED to be a Seahawks fan, and rooted for them whenever they weren't competing with Dallas; but, it wasn't until after that game, when I boxed up every single bit of my Dallas Cowboys fan memorabilia collected throughout the years, and mailed it to a good friend and fellow fan, who was stationed in Germany, that I finally felt like I was the real thing:
The 12th Chick!

On another note, I picked Derrick Coleman as my favorite player, tied with Russell Wilson, because we share a disability: bilateral hearing loss. I lost most of my hearing when I was a year old, due to an allergic reaction to medication, and have had to wear hearing aids and take speech therapy most of my life. I love Coach Pete Carroll, and have since he took over the team, because he's such an optimist, smiles all the time, and really respects his team and the game...along with reminding the players how lucky they are to be physically blessed to play a game he was ultimately too small for. I have no doubt that he gave Coleman the opportunities to show what he could do, and prove he could start as full back. Coach Carroll is an amazing and inspiring man, along with owner John Schneider and most of the team they've built, including QB Russell Wilson and Full Back Derrick Coleman.

note: I've been a Seahawks fan practically my whole life...or perhaps before I was even born.  The day before I was born my mother checked into Jefferson County Hospital in Port Townsend because she was pregnant with me and was close to the due date in December of 1984.  I remember my mother telling me when I was about 11 years old that while she was waiting to give birth to me, she put the game on KIRO radio and the call from the late, great Pete Gross and Steve Raible, who obviously calls the games today.  It would have been cool to have been delivered while the Seahawks were dominating the Detroit Lions that Sunday afternoon, but I wasn't born until very early the next morning.  Ever since then they've always been my team of teams (not trying to knock on the Mariners or Huskies because I root for them, too).  From the twilight of Steve Largent's career peak to the lean years under Ken Behring's ownership (and near-move to California) to Paul Allen's purchase & transformation of the franchise to what it is today.  Even after moving to Montana when I was seven years old I've never changed allegiances, not even to the hated Broncos!  I always have and will always remain a loyal & committed 12.

name: MaryAnne Wuennecke
note: When I made my HS cheerleading squad in 1984, I didn't know much about football, and I didn't want to be embarrassed by doing the wrong kind of cheer at the wrong time (such as "get that ball" when we were on offense) so I got my dad to explain the basics. I started watching Seahawks games every Sunday and I was hooked! When I was a college junior, I'd still never been to a game in person, and my all-time favorite player - Steve Largent - was retiring, so even though it was finals week in Pullman, I took a Greyhound over the snowy pass and was at #80's last home victory (against Bo Jackson & the Raiders). Several years later, as a small-town TV reporter, I had the opportunity to meet Mr. Largent when he participated in a fundraiser for a local politician, and he was one of the kindest, most polite gentleman it has ever been my honor to meet. Each time the team has won the NFC championship, I've literally cried, and at the end of Super Bowl 48 I couldn't even talk. I even bought myself a set of rings in green, blue, & silver engraved with the team name, which I call my SB ring since I wore them for the first time on Feb. 2 as a sign of faith. I still have the recording from SB48 on my DVR, and somewhere I still have a #80 t-shirt that I wore 30+ years ago.

name: Charles
note:
The Seattle Seahawks, my hometown team, won this thing called the Super Bowl last weekend. And no, the Super Bowl is not a superbly packed bowl of marijuana (although I suppose it could be) or a bowl of mixed mint chocolate brownie and coffee ice cream. It’s the trophy won by the best team in the National Football League for each season. 

A Seattle City Councilman once said that sports provided zero cultural value to the city. The 700,000 people who showed up in Seattle on Wednesday, more than the city’s population, illustrated the importance of having a team like the Seahawks in their city.

I moved to Seattle in 2001 after my father took a job with the Seahawks to be their Executive Vice President of Ballpark Operations, among other things. 2001 was also the year I turned 12 and started to go through that fun stage in life called adolescence. During my dad’s first season with the team, they played at the dingy Husky Stadium, and the Seahawks finished 9-7, missing the playoffs. 

And then finally, in 2002, the Seahawks moved into their new stadium, and the rest of the sports world could see the work my dad had put in to make the new stadium a brilliant place to watch a football game. My Seahawks pride burned as brightly as ever, with me mimicking the referee signaling first downs with my foam finger, and my sisters pretending they weren’t related to me.

During the 2003 season, in a bid to bring back the passion the Seahawks enjoyed from their fans during the 1980s, my father led the charge to create a “12th Man” flag. On October 12, 2003, the big blue banner emblazoned with the number 12 was raised for the first time, and from then on came to represent so many different people from so many different walks of life. I don’t think my dad could have foreseen the impact his idea would have on the region at the time, but it’s one of the reasons I smile every time I see it.

Eventually, for my dad, it was time to move on from the Seahawks and his unfortunate falling out with his employers and wrongful termination soured my relationship with the team, as you might expect. Their Super Bowl run in 2005 was bittersweet for me. I was rooting for the team because Seattle is home, but it was also hard because they had recently fired my father. 

But by season’s end, the wound had mostly healed. My dad and I went to the NFC Championship game that season to watch the Seahawks annihilate the Carolina Panthers on their way to the franchise’s first Super Bowl. The game that followed two weeks later was one of the worst sports-related experiences of my life. That said, I formed one of the best friendships I currently have with my friend Connor Folse, with whom I wrote an opinions article about how the Seahawks got screwed by the officials in that game. 

Let’s fast forward this a bit to 2011. By this time my father has been forced into retirement by a recent struggle with kidney failure, and has moved back to Seattle. The Seahawks finish that season 7-9, sneaking into the playoffs by virtue of playing in the worst division in football. Over my last winter break of university, I watched Marshawn Lynch complete that epic 67-yard run that caused not only literal seismic activity, but a real seismic change in how the city, and myself, viewed our football team.

That same year, I moved back to Seattle and started living with my dad. I requested Sundays off specifically so that I could watch football with him, because that’s what we did. Like pretty much any father and son, we bonded most when there was a game going on. I was especially grateful then to have the chance to watch games with him, as when he worked in sports I’d only get to watch half of the games with him.

As I think a lot of you know by now, my dad’s health situation has not improved. In fact, it has gotten worse and generally has been very difficult for my family and I to deal with. Football is incredibly valuable to us, it’s what brings us all together.

This Seahawks season was so special to me because of the people I got to spend it with, watching every week and yelling from the couch, skittles in hand. Even though I was living in DC, and my father was in Seattle, we’d still talk about the games, how we thought the team did, and we’d talk about his favorite player, Russell Wilson. 

During Christmas last year my family and I visited my father in his hospital bedroom. I’m sure most of you saw the picture of us together (it’s my default on Facebook and likely won’t change). Most of his gifts last year were Seahawks-related. He really does love this team. It was an emotional day for all of us. Spending part of your Christmas in a hospital is never anything you want, but on that day anyway I was very happy to do it, because we don’t know how many we’ll have left together. No one does, really.

The run the Seahawks made in the playoffs was special. The dramatic win versus the 49ers being the most prominent highlight of it, but the game versus New Orleans and the Super Bowl were also pretty neat. I just wished my dad could have been there watching these games with me. 

When the Seahawks won the Super Bowl on Sunday, the first person I thought of was my dad and how much it would mean to him. I was happy to later learn that he had been able to watch all of the game in spite of being in and out of being mentally aware. I wasn’t able to get a hold of him that night, and I really wish I would have been able to. He’s the person I’ve always shared moments like that with, and I really wanted to share this specific one with him. 

The Super Bowl win was also a validation of the pride I have for being from Seattle. No one really pays us much attention, and we almost like it better that way. Any time we make a claim to being better at something than another place, the other side tries to put us back at the kids table. Well, we’ve grown up now. 

Seattle is a bit weird. We put cream cheese on our hot dogs. Our musicians got famous off of purple haze, teen spirit, big butts, and thrift shops. We don’t do orthodox. We’re the reason the rest of the country is hooked on caffeine. You may have heard of a computer company called Microsoft, they’re based here. Mayhaps you’ve ordered something off a little site called Amazon, they were created here. And then there’s this team called the Seahawks, and they have a running back whose runs are powered by Skittles and cause seismic activity. Our fans set records for noise at stadiums. It’s also where I really grew up.

Last Sunday’s win was for my father, who has been through so much. The win was for my family, who have gone through a very tough year and needed the emotional lift of a Super Bowl. The win was for my sister Meredith and I, who watched nearly every game together. The win was for my friend Sam and I, who I watched every game but two with. The win was for my city, who had been wrongfully stripped of its basketball team, who had waited 30+ years for a championship many thought would never come. 

I think about it now, considering everything I just wrote, and it isn’t so shocking that the Seattle Seahawks are world champions. It really feels like we all earned it. That triumphant feeling will never really go away, either. I smile every time I think about it. And these days, I really need it.

name: Peter Tennis
note:
"This is the greatest day in Seattle sports history", I yelled as the clock ticked off the remaining seconds of prelude to the Seattle Seahawks  world championship win.  There we were, a small group of Washingtonians gathered on the other side of the planet, in the pre-dawn hours, watching the game live. It felt like more than a game. More than a sport. More than simply a hometown team. Seeing this win brought a visceral connection, an intense emotion, a gasping release - of vindication. Largent taught me to run. Zorn taught me to throw. Bosworth cut my hair. Patera and Knox taught me emotion. The Seattle Seahawks aren't just a football team - they are family. Seattle is family (at least until the people from CA crowded in and stopped being neighborly). And when Family comes out on top, after all these years, you smile. Because it doesnt change what you knew all along, it just lets the world in our your little secret.
And as I left the house that morning, under an Arabian sky where moisture is scarce and football nonexistent, the heavens opened and wept a Seattle drizzle, partly in joy, and partly in honor of those who, no matter where they are, are family.

name: Mark Arnold
note: I am 63 years old and a lifelong sports fan, particularly of the sports I grew up with—football, basketball and baseball. I was raised in the Seattle area and has lived here most of my life. As a kid, in the days before big time pro sports came to Seattle, I was an ardent fan of both the Seattle Rainiers minor league baseball team and the University of Washington Huskies football team of Jim Owens. Being tucked away up in the Pacific Northwest it may be odd but my real football love in those early sports years of the late ‘50s and early ‘60s, was the Baltimore Colts of Johnny Unitas, Raymond Berry, Gino Marchetti, Big Daddy Lipscomb and Lenny Moore. It was through watching and reading about them that I learned to love professional football. Growing up in a family of six kids it was never easy, but every time I could I would watch the Colts on the old family black and white TV, rabbit ears and all. There was as much excitement then watching that old antique as there is now watching the Hawks on a flat screen Hi Def. (It really is the game that counts.) When the Seahawks arrived in Seattle in 1976 I was an instant fan of the team, though at the time the Baltimore Colts of Bert Jones, Roger Carr and Lydell Mitchell were becoming good again and required an eye trained on them in the sports pages. When Baltimore owner Robert Irsay packed up the team and ripped it off to Indianapolis in the early ‘80s my Colts ties were severed for good, but by then I was bleeding Seahawks blue and green anyway. Like many Seahawks fans in Seattle, who have loved the team from the start and who pre-date even the “twelfth man” fanaticism of today, I have gloried in every high the team had, and suffered with every low; all of which makes this Super Bowl winning season sweet and something never to be forgotten. None of the 700,000 plus “twelves” who packed downtown Seattle on the Wednesday following our team’s 43-8 Super Bowl beat down of the Denver Broncos ever will. In 2014 let's do it again! Go Hawks!! MA

name: Dane Siegfried
note: I'm a dedicated Seahawks fan from Bellingham, Washington. My first memories of the hawks are watching Joey Galloway streak down the sideline for touchdowns. I remember how bad it stung watching our Seahawks lose the Super Bowl during my freshman year of high school. Watching our Super Bowl season unfold this last year was a lifelong memory, and it's amazing to see the hawks affect an entire region of dedicated fans. This last winter I graduated from Western Washington University with Bachelors degrees in both Communication and Recreation. Just a few weeks ago my girlfriend Lauren and I moved to Colorado, where we are attending the University of Northern Colorado (just an hour north of Denver). I am pursuing my Masters degree in Sport Administration. This is my first time leaving Bellingham, and I have never seen so much Blue and Orange in my life. I have friends and family back home who ask me if I'll become a Broncos fan. I look at them in dismay. I know a true Seahawks fan could never do such a thing. Although I am living in a different region of our country, I will never lose my Seahawks spirit. There was no better feeling than walking to class last Thursday in my throwback Jon Kitna jersey and Seahawks hat. Here's to another season of Seahawks success, and hopefully another Super Bowl!

name: Melinda Stearns
note: I grew up in Southern Calif., thinking football was a violent sport with all the shoving & collisions. I didn't understand it at all but my Dad & I had a ritual of watching the Rose Bowl together every year. On January 1, 1978, I watched Warren Moon lead the Huskies to a Rose Bowl victory the day before I started my career at Boeing. That changed my life profoundly! I was so mesmerized by this dynamic QB that I started learning all that I could about this incredibly Nobel game. I saw that it was not necessarily a 'violent' game, but admittedly  a 'rough' one. It took several years before I could afford season tickets and I had to go on a waiting list. I used to call the Seahawks 'My Men' but I keep getting older, and they don't. So, now, I call them, 'My Boys'. My passion & loyalty for them is enormous; I never felt a fraction of school-spirit that compares to 12th Fan enthusiasm. So much of my life revolves around team awareness: whether it is studying player stats, reading blogs, comparing Seahawks' team stats to other teams' stats, watching any Seahawks related programming, buying Seahawks' related merchandise, Tweeting about them, etc. I even record home games so that I can re-watch games I've just been at. This is helpful on controversial calls and particularly good games. As far as their current level of excellence goes - well, it's been a long time coming. We are so fortunate to have the 3 elements necessary for success: Owner, GM, Coach, all with Vision and willingness to recognize what others fail to see.

name: Danae Ayusso
note:
Growing up in Washington you never had a team to root for. None of the big markets bothered to look at the small market team from the Pac NW. I suppose that's where the 12's get their chip on their shoulders just as our Super Bowl Champions have chips on their shoulders: we were always overlooked and dismissed as just getting lucky.
When I met my husband 10 years ago, he wasn't entirely sure how to handle me. I yelled at the television louder than he did, I had a fish named Tatupu, and our son's first words were, "Damn it, Holmgren!" even.
When the Hawks went to their first Super Bowl, we watched up in Bonners Ferry with my husband's parents. They weren't entirely sure what to make of the blue hair, Tatupu jersey wearing, yelling at the third team on the field (the refs), woman. My husband made sure that we never watched another Seahawks game up there because they were scared of his wife.
Last season I predicted the scores of each playoff game (I was within three on each), and I even predicted the Super Bowl which my husband is still in shock over (not because we won, but because I predicted we'd score three ways and would score within the first 60 seconds, regardless of who had possession). This year I'm 1 for 1 on my score predictions (last week I said Green Bay would score first and fast, but they would be limited to 10 in the first half, they would score once more in the second, but the Seahawks would dominate the second half and win by more than two touchdowns). Once again, my husband gave me the look because even Vegas didn't have odds that specific. After the third quarter wrapped, he informed me I was a witch and I should stay out of Salem just to be safe.
Cheering from our living room for the Hawks is a family event. Our two sons join us (until they can't take the yelling anymore, then they watch the rest of the game in the basement), and it's....being a loud and proud 12th has connected us, via Facebook and Twitter, with other 12's around the world, and we've made many new friends because of it. Seeing all of the charity work the Seahawks players do only reiterates to us that we are cheering for a team that is more than worthy of being called world champions; they are champions off the field because of all of the charity work they do. 
We are proud to root for the Seahawks, and even prouder to be a loud and proud 12's.
Go Hawks!

Franco signed with the Seahawks and I followed him there. I have been a Seattle Seahawk fan ever since. I know bleed Blue and Green. Its so funny because I have been wearing Seahawk gear for years. For the most part people would say to me "Seahawks!" they suck!! I had to listen to it for years. The other thing about wearing the Seahawk gear is many people either said they suck or never noticed. name: Loreen Anderson
note: I am from Bremerton, but I moved to Virginia for 24 years.  I started flying home to go to games several years ago with my cousin.  I knew that I would be relocating back to the PNW, so I signed up for season tickets.  I had been told it would take awhile to get them. Imagine my surprise when Will called my from the Seahawks to tell me it was time to pick my seats that very year!!!  Now my dilemma of what to do!  I picked a pair of club section seats and then made a call to my cousin.  I told her I needed her help and that I had bad and good news!  I told her I was now the proud owner of a pair of Seahawks season tickets, that was the good news.  I then asked her if it would be a problem for her to go to every home game and to sell the extra ticket for the games I could not fly back for?  I think she is still to this day thinking I was crazy!  I flew home the first and second year for only one game. The next year I was so very lucky to come home for the last 3 games of the season!!  I then flew back to Virginia and it was time to drive to DC for a playoff game!  That was an experience of a lifetime, to only be followed by then going onto Atlanta.  I met so many 12s from all over and especially from home.  I then moved back to Bremerton and this next season began with a bang!  I attended every home game, including the playoffs and then was lucky enough to work it out to go with my cousin to the Super Bowl!  I do not think we can still believe it was real!  We are still riding high and I will always love the Seahawks no matter what the score of the game is.  They are my team and they play with all of their heart and soul and most of all they love the support that we as fans give them!

name: Brian Foreman
note: BLINDHAWK is what’s on my Seahawk jersey #12. I’ve been blind since childhood. It came on progressively so I had time to play sports—and I’m a fan of all of them—but football is my true love. Playing while I could still see allowed me to learn the sport, so when I go to a game, I can hook on my radio and follow along as if I could see while absorbing the fantastic atmosphere you can only get at the stadium. I don’t have a favorite player; it’s all about the team. It’s the ultimate team sport. I share season tickets with my good friend, Scott Firch, and have only missed one home game since 2003. I’m a licensed massage therapist and recently moved my business to Federal Way. It took a couple of months, but I managed to snag a new phone number with 1212 in it—just one of my many Hawk idiosyncrasies. As they say, “It’s only weird if it doesn’t work.”  My prediction is a second Super Bowl win—I think we are that good.

name: Volker Brunke
note: My wife drove me past by the pile of rubble, the day I immigrated to the USA from Germany, she told me, well Babe, that was the Kingdom and soon the Hawks will have a new stadium. she took me to my first game, Hawks vs Raiders, we lost that year, but the Hawks won, me as a true fan. I was fascinated of the speed of this game and what the players needed to do in a blink of an eye. I worked for a large IT corporation and had to fly alot, so I made it my lucky charm habit to fly in my Hawks colors, Hat, Hoodie and polo shirt. One day I flew from New Orleans via San Fran home. It was the first flight out, I didn't realize that it was the Friday prior to the division finals in San Fran of the 2012 season. I took a nap so I could beat on time while waiting to board. When I was called up for boarding I woke up and litteraly saw hundreds staring at me. I found myself wearing my Hawks outfit among 180 Saints fans bound for San Fran. I praise the lord, he made me 6'4" tall and equipped me with lots of humor. After all, it was a great flight, we trash talked a lot and had fun. 179 Saints fans and I, the only Hawk!! Needless to say, I love my Hawks, if they suck or win the SB, don't matter the hawks are my team. GOHAWKS

Some of the games that stick out (other than playoffs) were the win at Denver in 1984 on a missed kick by Rich Karlis, the win against Denvver at home in 1988 when Largent got redemption on Mike Harden, the heartbreaking loss to the Jets in 1998 and the phantom TD by Testaverde, a road loss at Baltimore in 2003 when we absolutely were shredding the leagues best defense, but couldn't get out of our own way, traveling to watch the win last year at Arizona when our fans basically took over the entire stadium... and the Monday night game last year vs the Saints when I got to take my own 8 year old to his first game and see the same look in his eyes, that I'm sure I had at my first game.  That was probably the best of them all!

name: Lee Turner

BUT ALAS SINCE I'VE BEEN LIVING OVERSEAS (10+ YEARS NOW IN INDONESIA) IT'S BEEN THE HAWKS THAT HAVE BEEN GETTING ME OUT OF BED AT 3AM EVERY MONDAY TO FOLLOW SUNDAY'S GAMES ON ESPN"S GAMEDAY.  WATCHING THEIR FIRST SUPERBOWL ON A COUCH PARKED IN THE STREET OUTSIDE UBUD'S FAMOUS NAUGHTY NURI'S RIB JOINT DRINKING BINTANGS AND WATCHING THE SUN RISE OVER THE RICE FIELDS PARTIALLY MADE UP FOR THE HEARTBREAK.  WINNING 5 MILLION INDONESIA RUPIAH  ($420) IN A NUMBERS POOL FROM DIE HARD BRONCOS FANS IN A SEMINYAK PUB.  WITNESSING THE AMAZING NUMBER OF TOURISTS FROM ACROSS THE WORLD WEARING SEAHAWKS T-SHIRTS AROUND BALI.  ENCOUNTERING THE '12TH MAN' DURING MY FREQUENT TRAVELS FROM SHANGHAI TO SINGAPORE TO SYNDEY, IT REALLY REVEALS HOW BOTH THE POPULARITY OF THE HAWKS AS WELL AS THE GAME ITSELF HAS TRANSCENDED BORDERS, CULTURES, AND BEEN EMBRACED BY SO MANY SIMULTANEOUSLY IN SOME OF THE WORLD'S MOST SPECTACULAR AND STRANGEST PLACES!   GO HAWKS!

name: Manny Harris
note: I was in the Navy in 1976 and since I was from Hawaii and we did not have a football team and the guys were always on my case, I decided I had to pick a team.  It just so happened that the Seattle Seahawks and the Tampa Bay Buccaneers were forming up teams, so I picked the Seahawks.  So, I have been a fan for as long as they have been around.  As it turns out, 2 years later, I got orders and reported to a ship stationed in ... guess where?  Of course, Seattle!  I spent the next 7 years cheering them on through every game, whether they won or (mostly) lost.  That's what true fans do.  I was walking into the game between the Seahawks and the San Diego Chargers a few weeks ago.  Imagine if you will, a Chargers fan looks at my nice new shirt and throws out a comment about my being a "fair weather" fan!  Ha.  His memory could only go back so far...asked me if I even knew who Shaun Alexander was.  I shot back that I did and told him I even knew who Jim and Steve were and let him know I was a fan before he was born.  Credit to other Charger fans, they told the kid to just keep quiet and go watch the game.  Go Hawks!!!

I have been to both Super Bowls; enjoyed NYC on the first row in the second level behind Manning in the end zone as he had very quickly come to know that force before the first snap...the 12TH MAN! Our communities young and old feel the dynamic and galvanizing magic of The 12TH MAN which the rest of the sports world admires. I've been a Seahawks fan since 1999, a few years after my parents moved us to Seattle. In summer 2012, I moved to Louisville, KY for school and I was dreading it in large part because I knew it was going to be hard to catch any games. Throughout the season, I watched as many as I possibly could, sometimes staring at the ESPN gamecast waiting for it to update, other times using websites that were not exactly legal. Watching games has always helped me feel like I'm not too far from home.

My wife and I both love watching games in part because of all the cliche Seattle B-roll that they tend to show (guy catching fish, people walking into the original Starbucks, another guy catching fish, shot of Mt. Rainier, more people inexplicably catching fish, etc.). It reminds us of how beautiful Washington is and how it's the home of World Champions.

We are headed to St. Louis to watch them play the Rams this weekend. It's our early Christmas gift to ourselves!

note:
The school i go to in Denmark, have a partnership with Edmonds community college in Lynnwood, WA. In October 2013, me and my class traveled to Seattle to study and live for two months. We lived with different host families and we had a great trip. Because i am from Denmark, i knew absolutely nothing about football. However, the community college planned a trip to the CLink, to watch the game between the Tampa bay Bucs and the Seahawks. Buccaneers managed to get a 21 point lead over the Seahawks, but the Hawks came back and beat the Buccaneers 27-24 in overtime. I have never experienced anything like it. At this point i didn't know a lot about football, but the atmosphere in the CLink was amazing, and we could definetely hear why the 12th man is the loudest fanbase in the NFL. I have been a huge fan since then, and even though i am back in Denmark, i now no a lot about this amazing sport, and with my gamepass, which by the way is very expensive in Denmark, i can watch every single game from home, and i love it.
Watching the amazing comeback win against the Bucs at the CLink was the most amazing the i have ever seen, and i will forever be a hawks fan!
And as Russell Wilson would say: ''Go Hawks''

name: Karrie Pavish Anderson
note:
I'm a lifelong Alaskan and a lifelong Seahawks fan. When I was about 5 years old, I'd watch football with my mom, and since she's a very patient teacher, I gradually learned football rules and fell in love with the game. My bedroom became wall-papered with any Seahawks photos & memorobelia I could find, from the cut-out photos from Seahawks calendars, to signed team posters, the Wheaties box with Steve Largent, newspaper layouts. No one could tell the color of paint on my walls - it was all just blue and green action.

When the 'Hawks played, I'd get home from church and skip the stairs at lightning speed so I wouldn't miss a second of the game, and if it wasn't on the TV, I'd sit in front of a radio speaker, just as content. At recess, I was one of only two girls who'd play two-hand touch football - I played wide receiver and corner even if I was in a dress. Corner was my favorite position.

Even though I lived in Anchorage, there weren't many Seahawks fans in my classes growing up, so often on Mondays, I'd generally be made fun of for sticking with my team. But I gladly defended with detailed stats and play-by-plays of Seahawks fabulousness even if they loss.

My senior year, I got a free trip to Seattle, so went with my Grandma to a game against the Broncos, my loathed arch-nemesis. I've been to a few games since and it excites me every time.

So now to the best part of the story. At the beginning of last season, I told my brother my pick for the Super Bowl: Seahawks vs. Broncos. He became a Broncos fan early on, solely because he knew I couldn't stand them! 

On NFC & AFC championship game day, my brother & I sincerely cheered for each other's teams for the first time. February 2 is my birthday, and I rallied lots of folks to cheer for the 'Hawks and Broncos so I could have my all-time dream Super Bowl match up on my birthday. 

Our village of Galena, Alaska is a small, fly-in-only community on the Yukon River. My friends don't care about football really, and I'd not met any Seahawks fans in Galena. So my non-football friends designed an awesome Super Bowl party for me, and folks who could care less about the Broncos or Seahawks made a Seahawks cake, Skittles punch, blue and green foods, wore Beast Mode eye black, blue and green ribbons in their hair and put up with my Skittle throwing and 12th-man shouting in the living room. A friend of mine painted my face for the event. And my brother sent me a crocheted doll in Seahawks uniform that I've named Richard Sherman Pavish Anderson; the doll now travels with me on the plane when I'm on tour. 

It was the BEST birthday ever because of good friends and flawless football by my Seahawks. 

Super Bowl victory over the Broncos on my birthday? I couldn't ask for more.

Except perhaps a repeat. #GoHawks

name: John Gallagher
note: My name is John Gallagher, and I am a college student at Grinnell College in the tiny town of Grinnell, Iowa, but originally from Mercer Island. Despite being born in San Francisco, and having lived in St. Louis, when I moved in 2002 and met Jim Zorn's son through soccer, my loyalties to the Seahawks since then have been serious and strong. However, in relocating to Central Iowa, home of many cornfields and few people, I found myself in the minority as a Hawks fan, until I met my friend Sam, ironically from San Francisco, but a die hard Hawks fan. Since then, homework is always on hold on game day, and the two of us cram into our dorm room, watching every play, every week, no exceptions. For us, the Hawks helped us become very close friends, mainly from being the only 12th Men in a world of Bronco and Packer fans. However, on November 16th, the dorm room and computer live stream won't be needed, as the two of us are day tripping it to Kansas City to represent our Hawks at Arrowhead Stadium, something we are both looking forward to anxiously. We may living in the middle of Iowa, but we do our best to rep the 12th Man loud and proud, and hope that we can do that for all of KC to see on November 16th. At least Jim Zorn will be proud.

The Superbowl victory was surreal! The parade was insanity! Now, I have taught my son about the Hawks and he is a BIG Russell Wilson fan! I hope I have instilled the Seahawk tradition into the next generation of fans! GO HAWKS!!!

Had season tickets afterwards and never missed a game. I'm a recent transplant to L.A. but am still whooping' and hollering from here.

name: Dan Roche
note: Been a fan since they came into the league in 1976.

note: Been a fan since the Seahawks beginning. Everyone wants to repeat, as do I, but 3 in 10 years is still a dynasty.

name: Jody Waldron, MD
note: I am working at a hospital in Kenya for the year via a University of Washington program. My friends are skyping me into todays game, and it reminds me of all the good times I had with the crew watching games last season. The Seahawks are helping me with my homesickness! Go Hawks!

name: Jo Scozzafava
note: When I first moved to Seattle in 1980, my in-laws were season ticket holders. I did not go to one single game because the game made no sense to me. Fast forward 32 years. A friend is a NY Giants fan (I am originally from NY), we watch Giants games together. He patiently explains the game to me as I ask every stupid question imaginable, such as, "How do they get the yellow line to move so quickly?" 2012 the NY Giants win the Super Bowl! Seattle could care less. I start watching the Hawks. 2013 the Seahawks win the Super Bowl. I watch a city burst with civic pride. I watch departments at the college I work at dress and celebrate. I watch how the spirit of the game brings people together. I am truly touched and in awe of the power of football, beyond the game itself. Now I get it! Go Hawks!

name: Wise Grandfather
note:
I watched the first Seahawk win ever on TV. 

Two most favorite seasons are 2013 and 1984.

note: I moved to seattle in the early 90's. I was 10. I live in Chesapeake, va now and watch the hawks games every week with some of kams high school teachers.

note: I love the Seahawks and they are gonna win the Super Bowl again! GO HAWKS!!!!!

name: Stephanie Kinney
note: BOOM! Whats not to love about the hawks??? born and raised a fan from Renton, WA

name: Bayan Saied
note: Been a fan since day one. Love the seahawks!

name: Dani White
note: Me and my husband LOVE the Hawks. They have been a passion we have shared throughout our whole relationship. In 2012, we got engaged watching the Hawks beat Green Bay in Mexico! This year, on July 4, 2014, we had a Blue Friday wedding. Him in his 12th Man jersey; me in my white dress, we said "I Do" as green and blue rally towels waved, and we vowed to always love the Seahawks, win or lose. We are true fans for life and will keep showing our support from Yakima, WA. Go Hawks!

name: Kayleen
note: Watch every game and support them no matter what. I have Verizon so I get the mobile app that I can watch their games live as well in case I'm not in front of or around a tv Love my Seahawks they are awesome oh and Pete Carroll too!

name: Lisa Valentine

Im from Seattle

name: Patrick Harris
note: I grew up in Bellevue, I started a meetup group here in the Atlanta area that has 85 members, most of us transplants.  I have been a diehard fan since the beginning, 76.

name: Brian Nicely
note: Though I don't in Seattle, they have been my favorite team and my sports passion since I was 11 years old.

name: Brian Nicely
note: Though I don't live in Seattle, I have been a fan since I was 11 years old. I just love thinking back on the days of Kenny Easley, Jeff Bryant and Jacob Green. Then about Cortez Kennedy and Chris Warren. Memories of Steve Largent getting crushed by Mike Harden and then him getting Mike Harden back! AFC West rivalries!! YES!!! Now that is big time / memory-filled football at its best! My heart broke when I heard that Ken Behring was moving the team to L.A. in 1997, so much so, that I flew to Seattle, got a hotel room, and spent several days helping out with the Referendum 48 campaign to keep the Seahawks in Seattle. I have so many lifelong memories from that experience! I got to hang out with Warren Moon and Big Sam Adams, spent some time with the SeaGals cheerleaders, was interviewed by the local media after they got word about my crusade and most proudly, got to meet personally with Paul Allen (how lucky are we to have this great owner!?) backstage at Union Station during the 48 celebration! Since that week, I have been fortunate enough to fly out to Seattle for two championship games, one in CLink and one outside as I couldn't get tickets! There is just nothing like Seahawks football! I now have a beloved and wonderful family that has sprung even more Ohio Seahawks faithful! My passion for the Seahawks has garnered many onlookers over the decades. Each and every game I get messages of some sort related to the Seahawks. We just absolutely love the Seahawks and all the 12's out there! Keep CLink rockin! We are proudly watching and cheering from afar!!

note: im a big secondary man especially the Safeties,when I saw the Legion against Atl. in the playoffs I thot they got robbed,been a fan since. still think they will atleast 3pete..

name: Kendra Woynarski
note: Grew up a football fan!  Moved to Vancouver in 2006 and got Season Tickets.  Every Sunday when the Seahawks are at home my husband and I set our alarm for 5am, and we are in the car by 6am.  We make the 2.5hour drive from Vancouver to Seattle.  We spend the morning with fellow 12's and then head to the game.  When the game is over we get back in the car and make the nearly 3-4hr drive home (longer due to the border wait and traffic).  We never miss a home game!  It's the one day of the week where we can spend the day together uninterrupted and in our favorite place.  When the Seahawks are on the road you can find us in our livingroom with our jerseys and hats on cheering on the boys.

name: Craig
note: Living in Germany is a blast and being in Hawk Nation wearing my #3 on Sunday's with a pretzel and Hefeweizen is awesome. Go Hawks!

name: Barry E Owen
note: I've been a fan since the first shovel of dirt was turned for the construction of the Kingdome - They had a helmet in yellow with a crown logo on it. My first Seahawk game was the first Pre-season game when Jim Zorn was tackled 2 yards from the end zone as time ran out. I thought they were going to the Superbowl that year (I was 16 at the time). I got my ticket from my sis who was an original SeaGal. I'm now in Woodway TX, watching over my Mom until I can return to the Pacific Northwest. Until that time, the internet, WiFi and everything digital is a wonderful thing to keep up on the Seahawks.

name: Michael Brown

name: Tony
note: Zorn (10) to Largent (80). Enough said.

name: Milissa W
note: The Seahawks and I were born the same years, I remember growing up in Seattle and later Spokane and watching years and years of Hawks games and many many great players.  It is great to watch birds I can be especially proud of living between two different birds of dubious fame.  Go Hawks!

name: Julie Larsen
note: My dad died when I was 30 and he was a season ticket holder.  I grew up watching the Seahawks when they weren't very good.  All but one of my children were born after my dad died and we moved to Colorado.  They are  diehard Seahawks fans. They have never been to a game.  It's like my dad is here every Sunday watching the games with us.  During the playoffs and Super Bowl last year, they faithfully word their Seahawks t-shirts and hats to school.  When the Seahawks won, they couldn't wait to wear their Super Bowl champion t-shirts to school.

name: S.E.
note: I work at a school, and being a Seahawks fan (even a pretty amateur, uncommitted one) has turned out to be a great way to get to know students I'd otherwise have a hard time connecting with. The connection mostly comes in the form of trash talking from San Francisco and Washington fans, but I'll take it! I met so many new kids the week I put out my 3D paper Russell Wilson figurine.

name: Don Kiser
note: Now live in Texas but still follow the Hawks closely.

name: lamar
note: Moved to Kent in 1988, been a hawks fan since 3rd grade. Through thick and thin, love the hawks!

name: Randy P.
note: Seahawks became my team in response to being in Bronco land and not wanting to follow the crowd. The Hawks were an expansion team and had really cool uniforms. Still do. Go Hawks!

name: Crist Jarrett
note: my first game ever was a playoff game in 1984 in the Orange Bowl. What young kid wouldn't fall in love with silver helmets? As a young kid from Miami, I used to try and convince my dad that a "Seahawk" had to be from Florida because the ocean was right here! It's hard to get up to Seattle for a game as a single dad, the last time I saw the Hawks at home was in the King Dome. Next week, however, I will finally get to see them in C-Link (and my Sounders the night after!)

name: Thielke/Gustafson family
note: Lived in Seattle for almost 30 years, now living in Chicago Bears land. Still loyal to the green & blue.

name: STEVE TROW
note: I USED TO LIVE IN SEATTLE FOR  15 YEARS AND SAW THE NEW STADIUM GO UP. GREAT SUPPER BOWL WIN!

name: Cary Tegarden
note: Down here in the Rogue Valley representing our boys in blue.

name: B
note: Being in Seattle when the Seahawks won the super bowl was a memory I will never forget.  The whole city was roaring from all the people crowded in the streets.  There was tears, smiles, hugs, and kisses from everyone.  Nothing in the world could replace the euphoria that everyone felt that evening from the win.  Every barrier human kind has put up over the years towards each other was tore down in those moments and everyone was connected, it was so beautiful.

name: Andrew
note: Fan ever since born!

name: Darlene Turner

name: Austin Hicks
note:
The year I moved to DC happened to be the same year our 'Hawks went 13-3 during the regular season, securing home field advantage throughout the playoffs. Knowing the importance of home field advantage, I was obviously thrilled. But I also knew that watching the Hawks rip through the playoffs - and doing so at the Clink, no less - was not going to be easy in a city full of transplants and fans of the team that shall remain unnamed. *Cue multiple episodes of intense jealousy over friends and family members living in Seattle, misunderstood outbursts of excitement by members of the DC public, and extreme bitterness at the nearly universal city-wide support of the Denver Broncos.

However, it also happened to be the year that the Super Bowl was being played in New York, a mere 4 hours away from DC. So, after Richard Sherman lit the world on fire en route to the Super Bowl, and after spending the entire season celebrating wins from my living room, I spent a small fortune on a bus ride to New York and a ticket to the Super Bowl.

The rest was history. Sweet, sweet, 43-8 Seahawk's history.

note:
When I left Kansas City for Oregon in 2007, I vowed to maintain my allegiance to the Kansas City Chiefs. The Seahawks were a dirty word due to the former divisional rivalry they had held with the Chiefs. That first season I maintained my position. Then, in 2008, I drove up for a Hawks game. I had prided myself in being a Chiefs fan - the best, most fanatical, and loudest fanbase in the NFL - or so I thought. 

That one game was enough. I saw unparalleled support of a team that was on the verge of making some magic happen. I fell for the Hawks hook, like, and sinker. I may still check in on the Chiefs from time to time to see how they're doing, but I couldn't tell you more than two or three of their players. The Hawks have turned my blood from red and gold to blue and green. Go Hawks!

name: Tom Riordan
note:
My earliest memories are of watching the Seahawks with my dad and grandfather. In elementary school, I remember being teased for remaining a Seahawks fan because each season they would usually end with a losing record. My senior year in high school we finally got to experience the Superbowl, and our state's first professional sports championship appearance since the Sonics lost to the Bulls in the '96 NBA finals. To lose a Superbowl in that fashion was excruciating. And for the refs to come out and apologize for their misconduct added salt to the wound.

After a few promising seasons we finally headed back to the NFL main stage and took the throne as World Champions. The resolve of Seattle sports fan base is second to none! Being a Seahawks fan for this long and watching the ups and downs with this franchise has been a wild ride, but well worth it. I moved to Capitol Hill last December and got to party on the streets after we won Superbowl XLVIII and partook in the parade festivities days following the win. I look forward to more Superbowl victories and Seahawks superstars filling the airwaves of local and national media!

name: Craig A Hansen
note:
When Seattle & Tampa Bay both came into the league back in 1976, I was not certain who I would be rooting for. A co-worker and I were at a place where we could not decide. So I decided which ever team got the first win in their history, that team would be my favorite. Once Seattle got that first win in their first season, I have been a faithful Seahawk fan. I lived in the Greater Puget Sound area for 19 years and attended several pre-season and regular season games.
The most memorable game was between Denver and Seattle in the Kingdome. The stakes were: the winner went to the playoffs, loser stayed home. Needless to say Seattle that year did not make it. I was in unison with many other fans over a very questionable call during the game.
The two greatest moments were when the Seahawks made it to the Super Bowl, twice. I was upset with accounts of the "Steelers/Officials" win in the first Super Bowl ever for Seattle.  The most recent trip to the Super Bowl was a most exciting for me, two scores within the first 12 seconds of the first half and again the first 12 seconds of the second half. 
My only regret is that my wife was not by my side to cheer her Broncos on and make Super Bowl Sunday an event like no other. My hope is that there will be other Super Bowl trips and most importantly, Seattle will stop being the training ground for athletes that get traded to other teams and do well for them!

note: Stationed in Washington and fell in love with the seahawks. Great to be a fan outside of Wa. 12's everywhere

name: Dott & Dave Thayer
note: We've been Hawk fans from the very beginning. We grew up in Snoqualmie Valley, lived in Redmond when we celebrated getting our own NFL team! We were on the 10 year wait list for season tickets when we finally got in! Our first seats in Kingdome were in end zone, had to sit with -ugh- Raider & Bronco fans! Over time we worked our way around to better seats, endured some pretty AWFUL seasons. I took opportunity to teach my daughter & son about football since my husband wouldn't go to games with me! When new stadium was built, we'd been assigned terrible seats, so I went immediately to ticket office & were able to upgrade to Club Seats, treated like royalty! We were offered use of Club area during non-game times, so we arranged our son's WEDDING in the Clubhouse on day Hawks were playing in Arizona .... in fact TODAY Nov 10 is their 12 year anniversary! Of course, I had insisted on having the game playing on all monitors in Clubhouse Restaurant, without sound, during reception. Our guests were thrilled to experience the brand new stadium .... which not have happened if I hadn't been such a diehard fan all these years!  We had to give up our season tickets in 2004 after we had to move to southern WA, but my passion has never waned!  I'd always claimed that "the year we'd give up our season tix is the year we'll probably go to Superbowl"..... which then happened! I felt so alienated from Seattle & the Hawk scene .. until this past Year of the Hawk & discovered all the fans in this "Portland area" wearing their Seahawk gear everywhere! Instead of people on the street simply saying "hello" or "how are ya" they say GO HAWKS! I love it!!!

Now my nieces have their own children and are raising them as Seahawks fans and I do my best to support their efforts.  I had the a wonderful day last February when I ended up on a flight to Seattle through Denver on Super Bowl Sunday.  I flew in all of my Seahawks attire and had a great time watching the first half in a Brew Pub in the Denver airport. I got to watch the 2nd half on a flight full of Seahawks fans and got to Seattle in time for the after game celebrations.  While my visit to Washington State that day was to visit my dying father, I rejoice in the fact that he got to see the Seahawks win the Super Bowl and I got to speak with him about the wonderful game before he died.  I  work with terrific group of people that despite the fact that none of them are Seahawks fans, decorated my office with all kinds of Seahawks posters and memorabilia which I still have up today.  While I am hoping for a repeat this season no mater what the outcome; I will always be a Seahawks fan and have been since their humble beginning!  
Go Hawks!!!

I won my first pair of tickets to a game by guessing the correct number of jelly beans in a jar when I was 7. My dad just as proud as could be escorted me to my first seattle seattlehawks game. We would go on to win and just like that the crowd thousands of other people sharing my interest I WAS HOOKED. 20 years later...I'm just as hard core. My right arm fully sleeved in Seattle tattoos, my wardrobe consisting of mostly blur, green and gray, down to my hair permanently dyed blue and green most of the football season. I truly love the Seattle Seahawks. They've made for some of the happiest memories I'll ever have. I attend at least one or two games every year and look forward to one day returning to the Emerald City so I can be at every home game. Good or bad. I'll always be a 12th man. name: Cedric Morris aka Hawk Father aka Feathered Defended
note:
I wanted to be just like Curt Warner when I was a young buck growing up in Salt Lake City, Utah.  #28 was plastered all over my walls and the SEAHAWKS were my team baby.  So I ended up moving to L.A. in 2000 and decided to start a Seahawks Bar out here in the SoCal.  So I did just that at a little place called the backstage bar and grill.  Started that 2006 and it's a place of destination.  When people come to L.A. from Seattle, they come here to rage with their fellow 12's...it's an experience!!!  It's packed every Sunday for the past 3 years with half the crowd being new peeps every week with some of the older peeps holding out because there was a worry that you wouldn't get in as the line would be down the block.  I also with my friend Travis Platt flew a GO HAWKS 12's banner over the last game we played at Candlestick Park last year, just to give our boys a spark during that away game against our #1 RIVAL.  I feel some sort of way about the 49ers.  Mama Sherman is the Chunky Soup "Mama" via a campaign I start September 2013 to get her recognized by Chunky Soup and to get her and Richard as the next "Mama's Boy"...needless to say, it worked man. And they cast me in the commercial as the Feathered Defender.  Oh yeah Baby...it's been a wild ride and the ride aint over!!! SEAHAWKS for LIFE!!!  Can I get an GO HAWKS!!! That reminds me, time for a prayer and the 12th Man Commandments:                  12th Man NFL Prayer
If it's NFL Sunday Football... then it's time to start the day off right with a NFL prayer!!! Whether you're a 12th Man fan or lesser thereof, the NFL is worthy of a few words.
Bow your heads as Deacon Jones leads us in prayer.
It's NFL Sunday PEOPLE!!! WAKE UP!!!!!!! WAKE UP I SAID!!!
Give praise to those that have made all of this possible, and breathed life into and onto man kind when we were amongst our darkest of ages. WAKE UP I say, and glorify their names people...why it's a glorious bunch, and indeed they are a glorious bunch. Say Vince Lombardi's name loudly and clearly...holla Papa Bear Halas's name in praise...scream out the names Tex Schramm and Lamar Hunt, for they merged two religions together to make a more perfect one...shout out the name Pete Rozelle, for he was THE most perfect Shepard...yell Steve Sabol's name, for he keep beautiful records of thy religion as it unfolded. All of these deities have blessed us with this wonderful religion... THE NFL!!!...praise them!!!! Look up to the heavens and know that Vince Lombardi is casting a smile 6 feet in your direction, and surely, it's not a dream...Yeah Yeah!!! 
Amen
Can I get a Go Hawks?
Can I get a GO HAWKS?
-Cedric James Morris           12th Man Commandments

1. Always stay completely and absolutely sucka free.
2. Never kiss your bicep, left nor right.
3. After each and every conversation say Go Hawks.
4. No matter where you are on Game Day... Be loud!!!!
5. If you go to Starbucks or any place were they ask for your name, tell them Go Hawks.  That way when you order is ready they'll call out...GO HAWKS!!! 
6. After each and every Beast Mode touchdown a skittle must be consumed, thrown, or the bag shaken.
7. On Friday's you must wear blue and type or say Happy Blue Friday to another Seahawks fan.

Examples:
If you see a 49er fan on the elevator you're about to get on, wait for the next one...you just stayed sucka free.

If you're working out in the gym, and you barely squeezed out that last curl, resist the temptation and just drop the dumb bell...you just avoided kissing your bicep.

If you're in a elevator with one other person at 5:25 pm on Monday and the game is about to start, turn to he or she and start yelling Rus-sell Wil-son chants while staring at he or she.  When the elevator hits the ground level, say, "Go Hawks"...you have now met the LOUD requirement while also satisfying the GO HAWKS statute.

You are now LOUD and PROUD my friend.
GO HAWKS!!!!

name: James Espinosa
note:
It was a typical day in College Station, Texas; I did some studying, a little drinking.
 
My buddies Zach and Michael invited me to the friend’s apartment for the Dallas Cowboys game.  (Side note: From birth, I was raised to be a Cowboys fan.  It was just as important to my family as me being raised Catholic.)
 
Little did I know, that day, that game, that feeling, would change my life forever.
 
It was a so-so game until the 2nd quarter, granted Emmitt Smith had potential to break Walter Payton’s rushing record; then quarterback Trent Dilfer suffered an achilles injury.  He would not return.
 
Matt Hasselbeck relieved Trent.  He went on, 12 for 19, 131 yards, and 1 INT.  Not bad for a Boston College kid who just got thrown into a game against one of the best teams in the NFL.  Mike Holmgren stated after the game “He is a player that gets excitable, but he played well within himself today…”
 
Shaun Alexander (soon to be Pro Bowler and on the cover of Madden 2007) rushed 23 times for 58 yards.  His 2-yard touchdown run made it 7-0 with 12 seconds left in the first half and a 5 yard TD run made it 14-7 early in the 4th quarter.

A hit by Darren Woodson on Dallas' Darrell JAckson almost made me piss my pants.  Knocked the CRAP outta him and I, till this day, cannot get that image out of my head.  Why would I want to?!  Go Hawks! 
 
Emmitt Smith tied the game with a 1 yard TD run, marking his 150th career rushing score, at the end of his record-breaking drive.
 
Seattle’s ensuing drive went 72 yards, to set up Rian Lindell’s game winning kick.
 
I was speechless.  For some strange reason I was completely enthralled.  I had a feeling expand inside of me and I was just taken back.
 
Hasselbeck, the golden boy from B.C., and the Alabama RB, Shaun Alexander, along with what some would deem as a below average defense and a lacking O line and WR core, pulled it out against some of the world’s elite!
 
Then thereafter the game was a concrete memory.  Then in 2005, Lofa Tatupu was selected 45th overall in the second round by the Seahawks, out of (Pete Carroll’s) USC, and I was sold.  The addition of Deon Branch and Nate Burleson made all the more worth while for me!
 
I have been, and forever will be, a 12th man flag flyin’, loud and proud, win, lose, or tie, Seattle Seahawks fan until I die, and beyond.
 
With this story all I have to say is “Stay true to your team, and never give up!” God Bless and Go Hawks!

name: Andrea Marshall
note: I moved to Seattle from Dallas in 1986 and it took a while to become a fan, but I didn't become a fanatic until the 2013-14 season, when I started following every game. I don't consider myself a bandwagon fan, however b/c I've never lost faith in my team, even in the darkest of seasons. But when I started following the players Facebook pages, I realized what a wonderful and talented group of guys we have in Seattle. Russell Wilson is the most inspiring man, taking time out from his busy schedule to visit kids at Children's Hospital and being such a kind and generous soul. I love his attitude and I love to watch him give interviews b/c he's genuinely friendly. He's one of the few athletes who will greet the media before answering questions. Most just go up to the microphone and start talking.He's so positive and upbeat, even after a loss and he jsut focuses on starting again, taking the blame for himself. But when it's a win, he won't take the credit, he says it's a team effort. He really impressed me when he was interviewed after the Superbowl on David Letterman. David was trying relentlessly to get Russell to say something negative about Peyton Manning and Wilson showed extraordinary class in saying only positive things about his opponent. I love that Richard Sherman, Doug Baldwin, Earl Thomas and Derek Coleman all have charities in their names. We are blessed in Seattle to have such wonderful players and even if they don't win another Superbowl this year, they are still champions in my eyes. Go Hawks!

name: Annuncia Case
note: I am over 55yrs old and have never been interested in football, until the tremendous support from my 1,000+ co-workers. During the weeks before the Superbowl in NY, the entire Agency was electrified with the Seattle Seahawks. I was scheduled to babysit my grandtriplets that week of the SB in Maryland. I bought my first Seahawks clothing, a Seahawks Superbowl sweatshirt and brought it with me to MD. I watched the game that night and realized that I was in the game full blast with intensified hopes for the Seahawks to win. There was so much exploding energy of hopes in me for the team. What made me so involved was the fact, that the media never really focuses on them, but the opposing team.  Even more so, I was totally bothered by the pilot on my flight wearing a Peyton Manning jersey.  My mind was energized with streaks of power for the Seahawks team. I did not understand the game, but I knew they had to bring that ball to the other end and prevent the opposing team from entering their end and make their points/numbers higher than the other team. They won and to this day, I still do not fully understand the game. However, I feel for each and every member of the team as I feel they are too often not recognized. What the world does not know, that IN EACH and every member is a pitbull trait - loving/caring; yet, a fighter to the end ENDURING EVERY PAIN AND NOTHING STOPS THEM. Each and every member must fight for himself, his team, and what they stand for S-E-A-T-T-L-E.

name: Randy
note:
I grew up in San Francisco and a huge 49er fan rooting for Joe Montana, Jerry Rice, and all the Super Bowl teams through the 80s and early 90s. I moved to Seattle in 1991. When the Hawks joined the NFC West in 2002 and got to play the Niners in the new stadium, I asked a friend who lives here - and also an avid Niner fan - to go to the game which was a week away at the time. We needed a pair of tickets, but the game was sold out. The Seahawks ticket sales person said jokingly that the only way to get into the game was if we bought season tickets. Being die hard fans, we bought a pair of season tickets. We figured we'd go to the game and sell the other tickets. The Niners won that game, but we didn't sell the other tickets. We ended up going to other home Hawk games and justified rooting for the Seahawks since they were our home town team. We cheered in lukewarm fashion that year but had fun in the great atmosphere of Seahawk Stadium. The following year, we figured we'd hang on to the tickets and go to the Niner game again and maybe some other games. We ended up going to all the home games. In fact, we slowly supported the Hawks more and more. That second year, we cheered for the 49ers but it was difficult given we had been cheering for the Seahawks too. The 3rd year of our season tickets, we more or less cheered for the Hawks over the Niners when that game came around. It was kind of like cheering against your best friend so you could cheer for your own kid. Fast forward to today, and we're both die hard 12s. I went to the Super Bowl last year with my son and had the best time that will last a lifetime. And my buddy who originally bought tickets with me upgraded his seats to the club level. 

Go Hawks!

name: Robert Quinn
note:
The NFL gained popularity in the mid 80's and as a 16 year old life was a little dull on Sunday evenings in the Autumn and Winter months. In those days we only had 4 TV channels and at 6pm, 2 programmes were about religion and the 3rd was about money - subjects that were not particularly interesting to me. The 4th however was a highlights show of American Football and I was instantly fascinated not only by the game, but of America!
The quick decision making, the attention to detail, it was all black and white. No 'grey' to waste time arguing about..... and this was the country, not just the game!
To my delight I found that a few of my college friends also suffered the same boredom on sunday evenings and they were hooked too.... but maybe not with the same fascination with the country however.
But what about a team?!
All the guys had got theirs - obvious choices such as New England and Dallas, but I wanted to be different and so in 1 class of History Modern World (I remember the moment till this day :)) I scanned down a list of all the teams until I stopped at the Seattle Seahawks.
Seee at le.... Just the sound of it got me! "Seeeaattle". That was it, that was my team and so the love affair, the fanaticism and the inevitable stress of following the Seattle Seahawks began.
For the next 8 years or so I only had a weekly highlights show and the odd live game to keep me going visually, however it was Armed Forces Radio that can best describe how much I was hooked on the NFL. 
The quality of sound back then was awful.... 2 minutes of crackle, fuzz and maybe even an Indian radio station but then I would get a minute of "Westwood One" as I think it was back then and oh was it beautiful. Listening to real live scores and action as it happened. It gives me goosebumps to think how I would here if Seattle had scored a touchdown and even win. (As you know there wasn't many in the early 90's)
I can still remember listening to my first live Seattle game on AFN against the Bengals at 2am on Monday or Tuesday morning in 1990 - we won 31-16 and remember knocking over my midnight orange juice all over my stereo speaker in jubilation!
The best or worst example (however you want to look at it) of my fanaticism was when some years later we had a power cut in the home one winters evening, whilst Seattle were live on AFN playing the Raiders, and so rather than miss anything, I proceeded to sit and listen in my car from 2 till 4am on a snowy winters morning. I took a blanket because I didn't want to keep the engine running with the heater on and maybe wake the neighbours!
I won't bore you with all that has happened since but suffice it to say I have been fortunate enough to attend in person both NFC Championship Games in Seattle, 2006 and 2014 and witnessed the Hawks comeback against the Texans, in Houston last year.
Whilst that doesn't sound a great deal to probably a lot of my fellow peers, its because I have used a lot of my travel time to try and see a game at every NFL stadium and with my love of America, every baseball stadium! Altogether I'm up to 25 total stadiums.
Seattle is an amazing city and a brilliant franchise to follow and I am immensly proud to be associated with it.
Yes more recently there have been some fantastic highs but those early years of losing somehow made my support even stronger and I whilst I may not get so down about a loss as I used to, it still is an amazing feeling getting fired up for every tackle, catch and run the guys make. 
Thank you for changing my life all those years ago and giving me so many wonderful moments to treasure.

My Seahawks adventure has just finished in spectacular fashion as my brother and I travelled from London to Seattle on Wednesday 19th November to fly into town for the crucial Cardinals divisional match. CenturyLink is the most memorable and my favourite stadium experience of all time, I've witnessed Soccer finals, Rugby finals but nothing in sport could compare with the noise, energy and pure volume that is brought by the 12s for our Seattle Seahawks. 

Everything from Touchdown Experience zone from 10am in the morning, facepainting, chanting, sharing stories and engaging with all the other Seattle faithful put not only the Seahawks but also CenturyLink Field at the top of any sports event I’ve ever attended.

Our trip didn’t finish there as we started the long road to Santa Clara to follow the Seattle Seahawks to face the 49ers at Levi’s Stadium on Thanksgiving Thursday, we witnessed another brutal performance from the Hawks and their LOB defence! It was amazing to see so many 12s make the journey to California and no matter where you are whether it be in the Pacific NorthWest or California, 12s stick together and root for the Hawks. 

Our trip was topped off by being able to meet not only my favourite Seahawk but also a gift to take home in which Doug Baldwin and Bobby Wagner signed my hat to take back across the Atlantic for life.

I wish to return to CenturyLink Field in the very near future and will do my best to spread the good word of the 12s and cheer on the Hawks to Superbowl Glory in Arizona!

GO HAWKS.

name: Marilyn Junkersfeld
note:
I moved to Western Washington in 1976 and one of the first things I learned about my new home was that there was a brand new football franchise in Seattle. Having been a lover of football since my high school cheer leading days, I immediately became a fan. I loved watching Jim Zorn and Steve Largent in action, but just as entertaining was Efrem Herrera's kicking and the trick plays the team often tried. (It seemed like they lost most of the time anyway, so why not?)  In the early eighties the team started winning. My husband loves telling about the time in December, 1984 when we got married.  Everyone was inside the church ready to start the ceremony, but they couldn't find me, the bride.  I was sitting in the car listening to the radio broadcast of the Seahawks playing the Raiders!  (They did get me inside eventually.  We got married, and the Seahawks won!)
 We moved to Florida in 1989 and stayed up late on work nights on the rare occasions the Seahawks were broadcast in the east.  I was watching them on Monday Night Football in Florida in '89 the night Largent retired.  We were so homesick we returned to Western Washington in 1990 and resumed following the Seahawks without missing a beat by buying season tickets shortly after.  There were some very lean years for the Hawks in the 90s, and I got tired of people saying, "Oh, I'm sorry" or "too bad" when I said I was a Seahawk fan.  I admit, there were a few times when I said I was going to "swear off forever"; but I just couldn't stop loving my Seahawks.
  In 2005, I told my husband (and others), "I just want the Seahawks to go to the Super Bowl before I die".  Of course, they did go that season and that made me a little nervous.  When they lost to Pittsburgh, I changed my bargain with God to, "I just want the Seahawks to WIN the Super Bowl before I die".  And last year, they did.  Maybe it's dumb to have tears come to your eyes when your team wins, but I admit my eyes got leaky when my beloved Hawks became Super Bowl champions in 2013.  It really was a highlight of my life that I'll never forget, no matter HOW long I live!  I'm glad I stuck with the home team through good seasons and bad, no matter how painful the losses were at times, so I can say I never gave up on the Seattle Seahawks.  They have made me proud, not only on the field but for the work they do in the community and the example of integrity they set for the new generation of fans.  Go Hawks!
