name: Chip
note: Born in Seattle, lived there when the Hawks were born. I was lucky to go to several games in the Kingdome.  Enjoyed the days of Jack Patera, Efren Herrera, Jim Zorn, Steve Largent, Dan Doornink, and then later Shaun Alexander and Hasselbeck. SB XL: end zone pass interference? low block called on Hasselbeck?  that was a fantastic season though. Then, 2013, I cried at the end of NFC championship, jumping up and down like a wildman in Portland after the game ending interception. After the SB win, I didn't stop wearing my Hawks shirt and hat for a week.  Finally, I just had to wash the shirt.  We did have a big SB party - if Bronco's fans showed up (they didn't) they would have been allowed to listen to game via radio in the backyard, and had scheduled times of being allowed to the food table. Ha!  I've rooted for the Hawks while living in Seattle (of course), Berkeley (took lots of heat from Niner's fans there), Philadelphia (had to break a 9 yo boy's heart once, when I told him I would root for the Hawks over the Eagles), and now from Portland, where thankfully, I have again found like minded fans!  I wore my Hawks hat in the presence of my mother-in-law this past summer, and she was amazed at how many people exchanged with me a "go Hawks" greeting. But, true fans understand that!  It is a common bond!  The Hawks current group - what an inspiration. From the hard knocks of early life, to his current success, Sherman highlights the value of a loving protective family to get him out of a hard childhood.  I love Wilson's trademark "why not us?" phrase in applying it to my own personal goals (e.g. my first Sea to PDX bike ride the past summer!).  Earl Thomas preaching teamwork and just having fun, really applies, I think, to making my own family dynamics succeed (wife, 3 kids).  Also, it is heartwarming to me to see my love for the Seahawks be passed down to my kids. Their favorite sports shirts are their Russel Wilson and Sherman Tee-shirts!  Someday, I look forward to coming up to Seattle and taking the family to a game!  The kids really want to go someday.  That day will come, when budget and time allows. Until then, we do have fun watching the games on TV, when we can (i.e. not attending to their own sports games). Go Hawks!

Having Holmgren be the coach made for an easy transition for my son and I since we had enjoyed the turn-around that he brought to GB. Experiencing the rise and then disappointment in SB XL, we were still hooked and have enjoyed the ride. I've always been a proponent of defense. My signature on seahawks.net is "If they don't score, you can't lose." When I coached, this was my favorite coachism. The Hawks have definitely proven that to be true. My son, and 2 year-old grandson, and I often watch the Hawks together as we did again last night. After his dad and grandpa cheer  at the TV, my grandson knows it's time for high fives all around. Go Hawks.

name: Christopher Price
note:
I lived in Olympia for a couple of years in the early 70's and watched the progress of the building of the Kingdome during my visits to Seattle. I love the Pacific Northwest and the traditional art of the First Nation people there. The original Seahawk emblem resonated with me from the first time I saw it.
When I returned to Vermont I discovered that being a Seahawks fan could be a bit lonely. I spent 8 years tending bar in a number of establishments, some that could have been templates for the movie Roadhouse.
It was not uncommon for sports discussions to grow in volume and intensity to the verge of physicality.
I could often defuse such situations by slipping into the gathering and loudly exclaiming "Hey, how about those Seahawks...!"
The results were usually puzzled expressions or blank stares followed by someone muttering "What's a Seahawk?"
I've been a fan for nearly 40 years, and my Seahawks have gone from unknown to unstoppable.
Go Hawks!

I traveled to Seattle in 2005 and toured the stadium and went to see them win against the Bears in the club level.  It remains my favorite vacation.  I have been trying to move to Seattle since my trip.  Being able to share your passion with the other people in the city is a wonderful experience.
